
 # GitHub Actions – Introduction to GitHub Hosted Runners

In GitHub Actions, workflows need a machine to execute jobs.

That machine is called a:

> Runner

GitHub provides ready-to-use cloud machines called:

> GitHub Hosted Runners

These runners automatically execute workflows without requiring you to manage servers.

---

# What is a Runner?

A runner is a machine/server that:

* Executes workflow jobs
* Runs commands
* Builds applications
* Runs tests
* Deploys software
* Executes scripts

---

# Simple Workflow Architecture

```text
Developer Pushes Code
          ↓
GitHub Actions Triggered
          ↓
Runner Starts
          ↓
Workflow Jobs Execute
          ↓
Results Sent to GitHub
```

---

# What are GitHub Hosted Runners?

GitHub Hosted Runners are:

> Virtual machines managed and maintained by GitHub.

GitHub automatically:

* Creates the runner
* Configures environment
* Executes workflow
* Deletes runner after completion

You do NOT manage:

* Infrastructure
* OS updates
* Security patches
* Hardware

---

# Key Features of GitHub Hosted Runners

| Feature                | Description                        |
| ---------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Fully managed          | GitHub handles setup               |
| Auto-scaling           | Runners created automatically      |
| Temporary environments | Fresh VM for every job             |
| Multi-OS support       | Linux, Windows, macOS              |
| Pre-installed software | Git, Docker, Node.js, Python, etc. |
| Secure isolation       | Each workflow isolated             |

---

# Supported Operating Systems

GitHub Hosted Runners support:

| Runner         | Operating System |
| -------------- | ---------------- |
| ubuntu-latest  | Ubuntu Linux     |
| windows-latest | Windows Server   |
| macos-latest   | macOS            |

---

# Example – Ubuntu Runner

```yaml
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
```

---

# Example – Windows Runner

```yaml
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: windows-latest
```

---

# Example – macOS Runner

```yaml
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: macos-latest
```

---

# How GitHub Hosted Runners Work

When workflow starts:

1. GitHub creates temporary VM
2. Repository code is downloaded
3. Steps execute
4. Logs are generated
5. Runner destroyed after completion

---

# Execution Lifecycle

```text
Workflow Triggered
        ↓
Runner Provisioned
        ↓
Code Checkout
        ↓
Steps Execute
        ↓
Workflow Complete
        ↓
Runner Destroyed
```

---

# Why GitHub Hosted Runners are Useful

Benefits include:

| Benefit               | Explanation                    |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| No server maintenance | GitHub manages infrastructure  |
| Easy setup            | Start immediately              |
| Scalability           | Multiple runners automatically |
| Clean environments    | Fresh machine every run        |
| Fast onboarding       | No manual configuration        |

