# 5. Parallel Execution with Hosted Runners

Each job gets its own runner.

---

# Example

```yaml
jobs:
  frontend:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

  backend:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
```

GitHub creates:

* One VM for frontend
* One VM for backend

Both run simultaneously.

---

# Parallel Workflow Flow

```text
frontend job ───► Runner 1
backend job ───► Runner 2
```

---

# 6. Matrix Builds with Hosted Runners

Matrix strategy automatically creates multiple runners.

---

# Example

```yaml
name: Matrix Example

on: push

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    strategy:
      matrix:
        node: [16, 18, 20]

    steps:
      - run: echo "Testing Node ${{ matrix.node }}"
```

---

# What Happens?

GitHub creates 3 runners:

| Runner   | Node Version |
| -------- | ------------ |
| Runner 1 | 16           |
| Runner 2 | 18           |
| Runner 3 | 20           |

---

# Benefits

* Faster testing
* Multiple environments
* Better compatibility checking

---

# 7. GitHub Hosted Runner Limitations

Although powerful, hosted runners have limits.

---

# Common Limitations

| Limitation            | Description                  |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Runtime limit         | Max 6 hours                  |
| Ephemeral             | Data lost after run          |
| Limited customization | Cannot fully control machine |
| Resource limits       | CPU/RAM restrictions         |

---

# Important Note

After workflow completes:

```text
Runner is destroyed permanently
```

Files do NOT persist automatically.

---

